caption: Finally had a chance to visit the ROOF this past Sunday and i couldn’t have picked a better day to do so. The weather was perfect and the views were amazing. The setup was cool too. Would like to see a wider variety of food on the menu though. Will definitely visit again once this pandemic is over. Great customer service as well.

I showed up to the lounge with my husband and two small kids for an afternoon lunch and snack—not sure what to expect— we were just looking for a nice place to grab a bite! And honestly, we were treated with respect and felt extremely comfortable and welcomed. We had just been harshly turned down by another “nice” establishment and the accommodations that we received at the Roof were so pleasant and refreshing. My kids loved the place (obviously—it’s gorgeous!) and the drinks were A+. We will definitely be back for a date without the kids next time!

Had an amazing time at ROOF on theWit this past weekend (Saturday). My boyfriend and I sat in the bar area at a high top table, the views were amazing and everything was clean and spaced out well for COVID. We felt VERY comfortable. Extra props to our awesome server/bartender TANNER! he was awesome! We will definitely be back here just for his service. I requested that he make me an egg white cocktail ( I have been a craft cocktail bartender/ bar manager for many years) and the drink he made me was SO GOOD! He was quick, efficient and personable. Thanks again for such a great experience for our little weekend getaway in Chicago!

Terrible service. Menu is small. They lost my reservation I made on open table I called ahead because we were 10 min late due to an accident. They sat us for the wrong amount of people and when we told them instead of admitting they lost our reservation they stuffed us at a makeshift table not meant for eating in the middle. Then we went to use the restroom and left 2 full drinks we just ordered and our jacket so they'd know we were coming back and instead the moment we left we hear someone running to the women's restroom calling us and then they said it was for the jacket when we corrected them and said we'd be back. After coming out of the bathroom we come back to our drinks dumped and an empty table. None of us felt comfortable and it felt very much like racial profiling, after reading some reviews I definitely agree there's some discrimination and felt it necessary to add this. The receptionist at the hotel gave us a voucher but we won't be going back to top it off we waited 40 min for a valet to get our car when all we wanted to do was leave and never come back. Then I get an email from open table telling me I need to cancel next time because I no showed my reservation 😑 At this point I wish I would've so we didn't waste our time or money 🤷‍♀️

My boyfriend and I had the most lovely evening here. Staff is fantastic, food was lovely, and our server was kind enough to take a quick photo of us while they had a pretty full restaurant. Thank you all for being so fantastic.

"Actually, your time is up." This is unfortunately the only thing I'll remember about my visit to the Rooftop on theWit.  I was traveling in Chicago on my own and decided to enjoy a sunny afternoon on the roof. I was first seated indoor when I got there. After having asked if I could be outdoor, they kindly offered me to seat at a nice table not far from the sliding window. This is why I put two stars and not just one: service itself deserves more than two stars.  Here is what happened though. I had an appetizer, a pizza, a dessert, one drink and one cocktail in less than 60 minutes, which is apparently not enough to keep the pace and the manager happy.  Right after finishing my last drink, I was asked if I needed anything else. I answered that I was still thinking, as I just had my last sip. I was enjoying my time so I was ready to order something else when a waiter abruptly gave me the check while telling me ”Actually, your time is up”.  In those COVID times, I totally understand that time per table be limited. But this was not the case. The reason I'm saying that is that there were a few tables with people that got there before me and that obviously weren't told the same thing... The problem is that I was seating alone and that a table of 3 or 4 people is more profitable. I get it.  I feel nevertheless this is just rude and unprofessional.  By the way:  Food and drink were OK (don't expect something delicious, you obviously pay for the place — and it's alright).

I was visiting Chicago, from Boston, for my cousins 50th birthday. His wife booked a room at theWit, so that we could hang out after dinner at the ROOF on theWit. She planned this at least 1-2 months in advance. So that we would be in line with policy, she called ROOF on theWit prior to reserving a room, to confirm dress policy, whether reservation was required etc... It would be about 10-14 of us, depending on who showed up. It was going to be casual, just hanging out at bar. We were not all arriving together. When I arrived at the 27th floor, my cousins wife was engaged in a contentious conversation with the host, there were four other members of our party (two couples) waiting a few steps away. I soon learned that they were not allowing us into the Roof on theWit because we did not have reservations and our party was too large. She and I spoke with a manger and security, they both reiterated the same "policy". The situation became quite heated. She and I stood in the line and asked every single party if they had a reservation. There was even a bachelorette party, who did not have a reservation that was allowed into ROOF on theWit. The difference between our party and the other parties, is that we were all Black people. All the other parties were white people or not of color. We became quite irate, letting the staff know that what we were observing. My cousin was so so upset. She even called ROOF on thWit, while we were standing in the line and confirmed the policy. Again, she was told by Ashley, that there was no reservation required and the size of our party was okay. Once she realized, that it was my cousin, who had called, she said "Oh, I didn't know it was you." and the manager intervened. There was another Black young lady standing in the line alone. She had been standing there for quite sometime, I asked her why she was waiting, she sad she did not know. I asked the host, "Why is this woman standing here?", He said I thought she was with you. I told him that all Black people are not together and he then let her in. In the end, we knew that they staff had decided, because we were Black, they would not let us into the establishment. My cousin checked out of the Hotel and checked into another hotel and we went to another Rooftop bar. However, the evening had been ruined. The Hilton should be ashamed of themselves to allow such treatment of loyal customers, who have been doing business with your company for many, many years. I can't put into words how humiliating it is to be denied access to an establishment due to, clear discrimination. The staff of ROOF on theWit can denies this all they want.. However, we are all professionals, who are quite capable of deciphering discrimination from policy. Clearly the "policy" is for SOME but not ALL! Depending on the color of your skin it can be resurrected or put aside. I will probably never stay at another Hilton Hotel.

Before planning my event I made a reservation at the hotel for the rooftop and asked if guest at the hotel would be able to attend the roof and not be apart of my reservation if they wanted to, which I was told they could at a fee for men and another fee for women. I spent a nice amount on my wedding anniversary there and a room block of about 20 rooms. So I brought in a nice amount to this establishment. When the manager of the roof notice how many people were trying to attend the rooftop from my party, mind you these were guest of the hotel, I was told they would have to be added to my reservation at a rate of $75 per person, even though a worker told them they wouldn't have to pay because they were guest and it was based on first come first served but standing room only. The staff was very patient with our group , heading from the burbs to the city was brutal.  We were there to celebrate a birthday for dinner and ended up staying for the entertainment.  We ordered Venezuelan rice with chicken and chorizo. The small skillet is good enough for 4 ppl. We also had cucumber salad good enough for 2/3 ppl and the potatoes with an incredible sauce serving 2-3 ppl  Drinks were The daiquiri formerly known as prince and the frozen lemonade.  Desert was a blueberry crumb cake good enough for two. It was delicious and good enough for 2. The blueberry sauce mixed with a creamy peanut butter whip on the side was the perfect ending.  We stayed and danced away. The DJs were awesome and entertainment included a Bruno mars impersonator. So much fun.  Our waitress went from 4 stars to 2 by the end of the night we went from her being very attentive ,to then forgetting drinks ,adding things to our bill. But they fixed it right away and had it handled within minutes.  There is a lot of security probably due to the amount of bachelorette parties there. The security was attentive and really did a great job. They handled themselves very professionally.  Cute set up ,photo booth, entertainment,dinner ,dancing ...what more can you ask for. We were lucky to enjoy dinner with the roof top open.  Thank you again ...highly recommended!
